ProMED-mail Rapporteurs Mary Marshall & Kunihiko Iizuka

[The graphics are striking in their demonstration of the recent sharp increase in case numbers, a very concerning trend. And yet another unvaccinated health care worker has been infected, in Butembo, bringing the total to 98 health care workers infected. One has to ask why, when a vaccine apparently is available to frontline responders, would an unvaccinated HCW treat an infected patient unless they were unable to get the vaccination, and vaccinated care takers were not available. It does no one any good to have unvaccinated HCWs treating patients. - Mod.LK]


- 10 May 2019 Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=7f927ace72

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 9 May 2019:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 1649, of which 1561 are confirmed and 88 are probable. In total, there were 1105 deaths (1017 confirmed and 88 probable) and 444 people healed.
- 310 suspected cases under investigation;
- 23 new confirmed cases, including 5 in Katwa, 5 in Butembo, 2 in Kalunguta, 2 in Mandima, 2 in Mangurudjipa, 2 in Musienene, 2 in Mabalako, 2 in Lubero and 1 in Beni;
- 9 new confirmed case deaths, including 8 community deaths, 2 in Mandima, 2 in Kalunguta, 1 in Mabalako, 1 in Musienene, 1 in Beni and 1 in Lubero; 1 death at Katwa CTE;
- 22 new validated cases, including 12 in Vuhovi, 3 in Katwa, 2 in Kalunguta, 2 in Lubero, 2 in Masereka and 1 in Biena;
These are community deaths that occurred between 30 Jan and 8 May 2019 for which it was not possible to obtain biological samples for confirmation in the laboratory but where the investigations revealed an epidemiological link with a confirmed or probable case.
- 2 newly cured, including 1 in Komanda and 1 in Beni.

